<ul>
<li><b>Split</b> <a href="" title="Category:Railway engineers">Category:Railway engineers</a> is (since Brunel) split into at least <a href="" title="Category:Railway civil engineers">Category:Railway civil engineers</a> and <a href="" title="Category:Railway mechanical engineers">Category:Railway mechanical engineers</a>, with little cross-over between them. <a href="" title="Category:Railway mechanical engineers">Category:Railway mechanical engineers</a> could split further to locomotive engineers and the others. Even people like Fairbairn did both civil engineering and engine component engineering, but were hardly <a href="" title="Category:Railway mechanical engineers">Category:Railway mechanical engineers</a> in the way that Gresley would be regarded. <a href="" title="User:Andy Dingley">Andy Dingley</a> (<a href="" title="User talk:Andy Dingley">talk</a>) 13:18, 11 June 2009 (UTC)</li></ul>


<ul>
<li><b>Support Andy&#39;s suggestion</b> -- <a href="" title="Category:Railway civil engineers">Category:Railway civil engineers</a> and <a href="" title="Category:Railway mechanical engineers">Category:Railway mechanical engineers</a> should neatly encompass all the people likely to have articles; and for the few (such as Brunel) who did both, they can be in both cats! It also avoids the UK/US terminology issue, since &#34;railroad engineer&#34; is clearly different from &#34;railway mechanical engineer&#34;. Splitting these further, by country, is unlikely to be necessary until there are sufficient articles to make it worthwhile (although UK/US sub-cats are likely needed from day one). -- <a href="" title="User:EdJogg">EdJogg</a> (<a href="" title="User talk:EdJogg">talk</a>) 13:52, 11 June 2009 (UTC)</li></ul>


